1    Introduction
A large literature has documented and analyzed differences in aggregate hours worked across countries (see
Prescott (2004) and Alesina et al. (2005) for two early contributions). In this paper, we document a striking
fact on the disaggregate level, namely that the cross-country correlation of average hours worked of married
men and married women aged 25 to 54 is essentially zero.1 Explaining the large differences in the labor
supply behavior of married men and married women with linear (average marginal) taxes – a prominent and
successful predictor in explaining aggregate hours worked differences in the literature pioneered by Prescott
(2004) – or with institutions, as stressed by Alesina et al. (2005), seems challenging. E.g., higher (lower)
average taxes should induce both married men and women in a country to work fewer (more) hours, which
is not consistent with the data. In this paper, we show that a standard model of household labor supply
together with a richer view of cross-country differences in tax systems, specifically in the tax treatment of
married couples, can account both for the pattern of differences between married men and women, as well
as for much of the aggregate differences in hours worked of married couples.
    Our quantitative analysis builds on the model of joint labor supply of married couples developed in
Kaygusuz (2010) and Guner et al. (2012a, 2012b). As typical for cross-country studies in macroeconomics,
we calibrate the model to match the labor supply behavior in a benchmark country, namely the US. We then
predict labor supply behavior in 17 European countries, holding preferences fixed but using the country-
specific economic environment. The latter comprises non-linear labor income taxes and consumption taxes,
as well as gender and educational wage premia, and the educational distribution plus the degree of assortative
matching into couples. For the non-linear labor income taxes, we implement th

